SIMD instruction sets:     Scheme  Target Architecture  Bit Packing Density  Storage Format       I2_S   ARM64, x86_64 (universal)  4 values per byte  Runtime quantized from activations     TL1   ARM64 (NEON)  4 values per byte  Pre-packed during conversion     TL2   x86_64 (AVX2)  Variable (2-way: 4/byte, 3-way: 3/byte + sign bits)  Pre-packed during conversion      Sources:       setup_env.py  61-64        utils/convert-hf-to-gguf-bitnet.py  801-810     Quantization Type Selection               Architecture-Specific Quantization Selection   The system selects quantization types based on CPU architecture detection during setup. The  SUPPORTED_QUANT_TYPES dictionary maps each architecture to its available quantization schemes.   Sources:       setup_env.py  61-64        setup_env.py  84-85        setup_env.py  109-151     I2_S Quantization        Format Description        I2_S (Integer 2-bit Signed) is a universal quantization format that represents ternary values {-1, 0, +1} using 2 bits per element. Unlike TL1/TL2, I2_S quantization happens  at runtime during inference for activation tensors.   Value Mapping:     0b00 (0) → -1   0b01 (1) → 0   0b10 (2) → +1   0b11 (3) → unused   Bit Packing Strategy               I2_S Block Structure by Architecture   Each byte stores 4 ternary values in 2-bit pairs, packed from MSB to LSB. The block size differs by architecture to align with SIMD register widths (256-bit for AVX2, 128-bit for NEON).   Sources:       src/ggml-bitnet-mad.cpp  12-15        src/ggml-bitnet-mad.cpp  51-196    Runtime Quantization Process        The  quantize_i2_s function converts floating-point activations to I2_S format:    Scale Computation: Find maximum absolute value across all elements   Ternization: Map each value to {-1, 0, +1} based on sign   Bit Packing: Pack 4 ternary values per byte using bit shifts   Scale Storage: Append scale factor at end of packed data    x86_64 Implementation:    For each 128-element block: For each 4-element group within 32-byte block: Shift group_idx positions: [6, 4, 2, 0] bits Pack into single byte at position group_pos     ARM64 Implementation:    For each 64-element block: For each 4-element group within 16-byte block: Shift group_idx positions: [6, 4, 2, 0] bits Pack into single byte at position group_pos     Sources:       src/ggml-bitnet-mad.cpp  51-96        src/ggml-bitnet-mad.cpp  151-195    Storage Layout               I2_S Memory Layout   The quantized data is followed by alignment padding and a single scale factor. Total storage overhead is 32 bytes per tensor.   Sources:       src/ggml-bitnet-mad.cpp  90-96        src/ggml-bitnet-mad.cpp  188-194     TL1 Quantization (ARM64)        Format Description        TL1 (Ternary Lookup 1) is an ARM64-optimized quantization scheme that pre-packs weights during model conversion. The format uses a complex tiling pattern designed for efficient NEON SIMD operations.   Key Characteristics:    Offline preprocessing during GGUF conversion  Optimized for 128-bit NEON registers  Supports configurable block sizes (BM, BY, bm, by)  Stores 2 ternary values per byte (4 bits per value: 3*value + 4)   Preprocessing Pipeline               TL1 Conversion Pipeline   The conversion process reads kernel configuration from  kernel_config.ini to determine optimal block sizes for each weight matrix dimension.   Sources:       utils/convert-hf-to-gguf-bitnet.py  479-520        utils/convert-hf-to-gguf-bitnet.py  465-477    Encoding Strategy        TL1 uses a paired encoding scheme:    Pair Formation: Group weight values into pairs   Hierarchical Encoding:  encoded = 3 * weight[0] + weight[1] + 4   Maps {-1, 0, +1} × {-1, 0, +1} → {0, 1, 2, ..., 8}     Reshape: Apply multi-level tiling transformations   Pack: Store high and low 4-bits in single bytes    Tiling Hierarchy:    (M, K) → (M/BM, BM, K/2) → (M/BM, K/BY, BY/2, BM) → (M/BM, K/BY, BM/bm, bm, BY/2) → (M/BM, K/BY, BM/bm, BY/by, by/2, bm) → ... (additional SIMD-aligned reshapes)     Sources: 